\details{
Specified by redesign Step 4.1. \code{eb_control()} itself runs no analysis; it
creates a validated \code{eb_control} consumed by \code{\link[=eb]{eb()}}, \code{\link[=eb_deconvolve]{eb_deconvolve()}},
\code{\link[=eb_test]{eb_test()}}, \code{\link[=eb_vam]{eb_vam()}}, and related helpers.

Per \strong{DEC-147-1} (replication-mode lock), when \code{replication_mode = TRUE}
the Walters-exact deconvolution settings are locked: \code{optimizer = "L-BFGS-B"}, \code{n_grid = 1000}, \code{n_knots = 5}, \code{mean_constraint = TRUE},
\code{c_grid = seq(0.001, 0.15, by = 0.001)}, and \code{seed = 1234}. User overrides
of any of these locked fields raise a warning and are coerced.

The \code{standardize} flag does NOT by itself choose a precision-dependence
model. If \code{standardize = TRUE} but \code{precision_model = "none"}, monolithic
calls such as \code{\link[=eb]{eb()}} skip the standardization step (no error). To get
Walters-style standardization, set BOTH \code{standardize = TRUE} AND a
non-\code{"none"} \code{precision_model}.

For the FDR surface: \code{pi0_method = "storey"} estimates the null proportion
\eqn{\pi_0} from p-values using \code{pi0_lambda} as the Storey threshold
\eqn{\lambda}; \code{pi0_method = "fixed"} treats \code{pi0_lambda} as the
user-supplied \eqn{\pi_0} and forwards it.

Setting \code{n_knots != 5} triggers a one-time message that the \code{numDeriv}
path will be used for derivatives; the hand-written Hessian/Jacobian is
only validated for the 4x4 case.
